Comprehensive Course on Lithium-Ion
Battery Technology and Battery Management
Systems (BMS)

Abstract
This course provides a thorough exploration of lithium-ion bat-
tery technology and the essential role of Battery Management Sys-
tems (BMS) in ensuring safe and ecient operation. It begins with
a foundational overview of lithium-ion batteries, covering key com-
ponents such as the anode, cathode, electrolyte, and separator, and
explains core principles like C-rate, SOC, and SOH. Learners will ex-
amine detailed battery models, including nominal voltage and typical
discharge curves, and dive into advanced characterization tests, includ-
ing OCV, capacity, and internal resistance testing. The course then
addresses SOC and SOH estimation methods, battery aging mecha-
nisms, and various diagnostic techniques. BMS topics encompass SOC
and SOH algorithms, cell balancing, current limitation, thermal man-
agement, and communication protocols. Practical elements include
a look at safety features, battery testing setups, and case studies on
SOH estimation using machine learning models like Random Forest,
Linear Regression, and Neural Networks. By the end, participants
will have a comprehensive understanding of lithium-ion batteries and
BMS, equipping them with the knowledge to enhance battery perfor-
mance, longevity, and safety in a range of applications.
1 Introduction
Lithium-ion batteries play a crucial role in modern systems, ranging from
portable electronic devices to electric vehicles [1]. They oer high energy
density and low self-discharge rates, making them a preferred technology
for many applications. However, the eective management of these batteries
1
presents considerable challenges, particularly in terms of safety, performance,
and longevity [2].
The objective of this paper is to deeply explore lithium-ion battery tech-
nology, their operation, and the Battery Management Systems (BMS) that
are essential for their optimal use. We will begin by examining the funda-
mental components of a lithium-ion battery, including the anode, cathode,
electrolyte, and separator [3]. We will then study the chemical reactions that
occur within these batteries and how they generate electrical energy.
Particular attention will be paid to the key characteristics of lithium-
ion batteries, such as voltage, capacity, and internal resistance. We will
also explore the concepts of State of Charge (SOC) and State of Health
(SOH), which are critical for understanding and eectively managing these
batteries [4].
The management of lithium-ion batteries will be addressed through the
study of Battery Management Systems (BMS). We will examine the main
components of a BMS and its essential functions, including battery state
monitoring, protection against abnormal conditions, and cell balancing [5].
The aging of lithium-ion batteries is a crucial aspect that aects their
long-term performance. We will discuss the factors that contribute to aging
and methods for evaluating and predicting performance degradation over
time [6].
Finally, the main contribution of this research will be presented: an in-
novative model for estimating the State of Health (SOH) of lithium-ion bat-
teries [7]. This model, developed from extensive testing on various batteries,
aims to provide a reliable and universal method for evaluating the health
status of any lithium-ion battery, based solely on global parameters. We will
detail the methodology used to develop this model, the results obtained, and
discuss its implications for the industry and future research in the eld of
lithium-ion batteries.
This study aims to signicantly contribute to the understanding and man-
agement of lithium-ion batteries, oering new perspectives for improving
their use and lifespan in various technological applications.
2 Introduction to Lithium-ion Batteries
Lithium-ion batteries (Li-ion) are widely used for energy storage in a variety
of applications, from consumer electronics to electric vehicles. Their high
energy density, long cycle life, and relatively low weight make them ideal for
portable and high-performance devices. Understanding the components and
chemistry behind Li-ion batteries is crucial for optimizing their performance
2
and improving their safety.
2.1 Components of a Lithium-ion Battery
A typical lithium-ion battery is composed of the following key components:
Anode: The anode is usually made of graphite, which acts as the host
for lithium ions during charging. When the battery is charged, lithium
ions move from the cathode to the anode, where they are stored between
the graphite layers.
Cathode: The cathode is typically made of a lithium-containing com-
pound such as lithium cobalt oxide (LiCoO2), nickel manganese cobalt
oxide (NMC), or lithium iron phosphate (LFP). The cathode is the
source of lithium ions and is responsible for the batterys voltage and
capacity. Dierent cathode materials provide varying levels of perfor-
mance, safety, and cost eciency.
Electrolyte: The electrolyte is an organic solvent containing lithium
salts (e.g., LiPF6) that enables the movement of lithium ions between
the anode and the cathode. It ensures ionic conductivity while pre-
venting electronic conductivity, which could cause short circuits.
Separator: The separator is a thin, porous membrane placed between
the anode and cathode to prevent direct contact between them, thus
avoiding short circuits. At the same time, it allows lithium ions to pass
through during charging and discharging.
3
Diagram of a typical Lithium-ion battery, showing the key components:
anode, cathode, electrolyte, and separator.
Each of these components plays a critical role in the batterys overall
performance and longevity. For example, advancements in cathode materials,
such as the development of NMC and LFP, have led to improvements in
energy density, cycle life, and safety.
2.1.1 Anode Material (Graphite)
Graphite is the most commonly used anode material in lithium-ion batteries.
It has a layered structure that allows lithium ions to intercalate (insert) be-
tween its layers during charging. The high stability and eciency of graphite
anodes contribute to the batterys long cycle life.
2.1.2 Cathode Materials
The choice of cathode material greatly inuences the batterys performance.
For example:
Lithium Cobalt Oxide (LiCoO2): Oers high energy density but
has limitations in terms of cost and safety.
Nickel Manganese Cobalt (NMC): Provides a balance between
energy density, safety, and cost, making it popular for electric vehicles.
4
Lithium Iron Phosphate (LFP): Known for its high safety and long
cycle life, but with a lower energy density compared to other materials.
2.1.3 Electrolyte Composition
The electrolyte in a lithium-ion battery typically consists of an organic sol-
vent (such as ethylene carbonate) mixed with lithium salts (like LiPF6). It
facilitates the movement of lithium ions between the electrodes during charg-
ing and discharging. The composition of the electrolyte is critical for ensur-
ing safety, as it can inuence the batterys thermal stability and resistance
to degradation.
2.1.4 Separator Functionality
The separator plays a vital role in maintaining battery safety. It must be thin
enough to allow lithium ions to pass through but robust enough to prevent
the electrodes from touching. Modern separators are made from materials
like polyethylene or polypropylene and can be designed to shut down the
battery in the event of overheating by melting and blocking ion ow.

2.4 Simple Battery Model
In the literature, a simple battery model is often used to represent the voltage
and current behavior of a cell. This model describes the relationship between
the batterys voltage, charge or discharge current, and its internal resistance.
A very basic model can be described by a linear equation, where the
battery voltage (V) is given by the dierence between the electromotive force
(E) of the battery and the voltage drop caused by the internal resistance (R)
during the passage of current (I).
The equation is as follows:
V=ERI
where:
Vis the voltage measured across the battery terminals (in volts),
Eis the electromotive force of the battery (in volts), often called the
open-circuit voltage (OCV),
Ris the internal resistance of the battery (in ohms),
Iis the current passing through the battery (in amperes).
This simple model can be used to estimate the batterys voltage during
charging or discharging, as well as to observe the impact of internal resistance
on the overall battery performance.
2.4.1 Nominal Voltage
The nominal voltage is the average voltage provided by a battery cell during
its normal operation. It is generally dened by the type of chemistry used in
the battery. For example:
A lithium-ion cell typically has a nominal voltage of 3.7V.
A nickel-cadmium (NiCd) cell has a nominal voltage of 1.2V.
The nominal voltage is used to characterize the overall performance of a
battery and is often provided by the manufacturer [1].
6
2.4.2 Voltage Variation as a Function of State of Charge (SOC)
The voltage of a battery varies depending on its state of charge (SOC). When
the battery is fully charged, the voltage is close to the maximum voltage.
As the battery discharges, the voltage gradually decreases. This behavior
is represented by a typical discharge curve, where the voltage drops more
rapidly at low SOC levels [2].
2.4.3 Typical Discharge Curve
The discharge curve of a battery shows how the voltage decreases with usage
(SOC). The shape of this curve depends on the type of chemistry used and
the operating conditions, such as temperature and discharge current [4].
2.4.4 OCV (Open Circuit Voltage) Curve
The OCV (Open Circuit Voltage) curve represents the voltage of a battery
when it is not connected to an external circuit, i.e., when no current is owing.
This curve is useful for estimating the state of charge (SOC) of the battery
without the need to measure the current. Below is space to insert an OCV

3 Characterization Tests
Characterization tests are essential for understanding and modeling the be-
havior of a battery. They allow us to determine performance, state of charge
(SOC), state of health (SOH), as well as other key parameters such as internal
resistance and capacity [5].
3.1 OCV Characterization
OCV (Open Circuit Voltage) characterization allows us to measure the rela-
tionship between a batterys voltage and its state of charge (SOC) when no
current is owing through the circuit. This test is used to establish the OCV
curve, which helps estimate the SOC without the need to directly measure
the current.
The OCV curve is obtained by allowing the battery to rest after each
charge or discharge step, allowing the voltage to stabilize.
This curve is then used to estimate the state of charge (SOC) from the
open-circuit voltage.
OCV Characterization Curve

3.2 Battery Capacity Characterization
The capacity of a battery is dened as the amount of electrical charge it
can store and deliver, expressed in ampere-hours (Ah) or milliampere-hours
(mAh). Capacity characterization is performed to evaluate the state of health
(SOH) of the battery over time.
Capacity is measured during a complete discharge cycle at a constant
current.
The nominal capacity is provided by the manufacturer, but it decreases
with the batterys age and usage.
Capacity Characterization Curve
3.3 Internal Resistance Characterization
The internal resistance of a battery is a key parameter aecting its perfor-
mance. It is generally expressed in ohms () or milliohms (m) and increases
as the battery ages. Internal resistance characterization helps estimate the
state of health (SOH) of the battery.
Measurement method: A brief current pulse is applied to the battery,
and the instant voltage drop is measured. The internal resistance is

3.4 HPPC (Hybrid Pulse Power Characterization) Pro-
le
The HPPC prole is a method used to characterize both the capacity and
internal resistance of a battery. It involves applying current pulses during
both charge and discharge to obtain a comprehensive view of the batterys

4 State of Charge (SOC) and State of Health
(SOH)
4.1 State of Charge (SOC)
The state of charge (SOC) of a battery represents the amount of electrical
energy remaining in the battery relative to its total capacity. SOC is ex-
pressed as a percentage, where 100% corresponds to a fully charged battery
and 0% to a completely discharged battery. It is essential for evaluating the
remaining runtime of a battery during use [8].
10

SOC can be mathematically expressed as follows:

This equation shows that SOC is adjusted based on the current passing
through the battery, taking into account its nominal capacity.
4.1.2 Coulomb Counting Method
The **Coulomb Counting** method calculates SOC by integrating the cur-
rent entering and exiting the battery. This method is based on the conser-
vation of charge and is calculated as follows:
SOC(t) = SOC(t0) + 1

4.1.3 Open Circuit Voltage (OCV)
SOC estimation can also be performed by measuring the open-circuit voltage
(OCV) of the battery. An OCV-SOC curve is used to match the measured
voltage to a corresponding SOC level. However, this method requires the
battery to be at rest to obtain a stable voltage [10].
4.1.4 SOC Estimation Algorithm
SOC estimation can be improved using advanced techniques such as **Kalman
lters**. The Kalman lter combines SOC measurements with a predictive
model based on the batterys state, correcting for measurement uncertainties
and providing a more accurate estimate [11].

4.2 State of Health (SOH)
The state of health (SOH) of a battery represents its degree of aging and its
ability to operate optimally. SOH is expressed as a percentage, with 100%
corresponding to a new battery and 0% indicating the end of the batterys
life [?].
4.2.1 SOH Estimation Methods
The methods for estimating SOH include:
Residual Capacity: Residual capacity refers to the batterys abil-
ity to store energy compared to its nominal capacity. This method
calculates SOH based on the current capacity:

where Qcurrent is the measured capacity and Qnominal is the batterys
initial capacity [12].
Increase in Internal Resistance: Battery aging leads to an increase
in internal resistance. This increase can be used to estimate SOH:
SOHresistance =Rreference

where Rreference is the initial internal resistance and Rcurrent is the cur-
rent resistance [13].
In practice, battery management systems (BMS) combine these methods
to provide a more robust SOH estimation [14].
4.3 Battery Aging
Battery aging is an inevitable process that aects the ability of batteries
to store and deliver energy over time. It results from various physical and
chemical factors that degrade the internal materials of the battery. This
aging can be divided into several main modes [23].
4.3.1 Aging Modes
Battery aging can occur in several forms:
12
Calendar Aging: This refers to the natural degradation of the battery
over time, even when it is not in use [24].
Charge and Discharge Cycling: Regular use of the battery through
charge and discharge cycles (including CC and WLTP cycles) leads to
gradual capacity degradation.
High Charge and Discharge Rates: Fast charging or discharging
can accelerate aging by increasing internal resistance and degrading
electrode materials [25].
Temperature: High temperatures accelerate undesirable chemical re-
actions in the battery, leading to faster degradation [26].
4.3.2 Battery Check-up
It is essential to regularly check the State of Health (SOH) of the battery by
measuring its electrical capacity and internal resistance. This allows tracking
the progression of its aging.
CAPA Check-up The CAPA check-up involves performing a full nominal
discharge at C/2 to measure the batterys current electrical capacity. This
method provides an accurate estimate of the batterys remaining capacity in
its current state.
DCIR Check-up Based on the Hybrid Pulse Power Characterization (HPPC)
prole, the DCIR check-up is used to measure the internal resistance of the
battery. The test involves [27]:
A constant current (CC) pulse for 30 seconds.
A 5-minute pause to allow the battery to stabilize.
Regeneration to the initial state of charge (SOC) at a constant current
of C/3.
An additional one-hour pause.
These steps help evaluate the impact of aging on the batterys internal resis-
tance and capacity.

4.3.5 Relationship with Aging Reference Points
Battery aging is often analyzed based on several reference points [30]:
BOL (Beginning of Life): The start of the batterys life, with 100%
capacity.
MOL (Middle of Life): The middle of the batterys life, typically
dened when the capacity reaches 80% of the initial capacity.
EOL (End of Life): The end of the batterys life, often dened when
the capacity reaches between 70% and 80% of its initial value.

5 Introduction to Battery Management Sys-
tems (BMS)
5.1 Main Components of a BMS
A Battery Management System (BMS) is a set of electronic and software
components that supervise, protect, and optimize the operation of recharge-
able batteries, primarily in industrial and transportation applications. The
main components of a BMS include:
Microcontroller: The brain of the BMS that processes information
from sensors and makes decisions based on the collected data. It ex-
ecutes algorithms for estimating the SOC (State of Charge) and SOH
(State of Health), as well as thermal management.
Voltage and Current Sensors: These sensors measure the voltages
of individual cells and the battery pack, as well as the current owing
through the cells during charging and discharging. This data is essential
for monitoring the batterys state and ensuring safe operation.
Temperature Sensors: Temperature sensors measure the heat gen-
erated by the battery during operation. Precise temperature control is
crucial to avoid overheating and extend the batterys lifespan.
Protection Circuit: It protects the battery against abnormal condi-
tions such as overvoltage, undervoltage, overcurrent, and short circuits.
It acts as a circuit breaker to prevent dangerous conditions that could
damage the battery or cause a re.
Communication System: The BMS must communicate with other
systems, such as the main controller of an electric vehicle or a charging
device. Communication protocols like CAN or LIN are often used to
transmit real-time information about the batterys state.
5.2 Main Functions of a BMS
The BMS has several crucial functions that ensure the safety, performance,
and longevity of the battery:
Battery State Monitoring: The BMS continuously monitors volt-
ages, currents, temperatures, and other key parameters to ensure that
the battery operates under safe conditions.
15
Protection Against Abnormal Conditions: In case of detecting
dangerous conditions (such as overcharging, overheating, or excessive
discharging), the BMS intervenes by limiting or cutting o current to
prevent damage to the battery.
Cell Balancing: In battery packs, individual cells may have dierent
charge levels. The BMS equalizes these levels by transferring charge
from the more charged cells to those that are less charged, ensuring
that all cells are used optimally.
Thermal Management: Thermal management is essential to pre-
vent excessive temperature increases that could damage the battery.
The BMS monitors temperatures and may activate cooling systems or
reduce charging/discharging currents to keep the battery within a safe
temperature range.
Communication with External Systems: The BMS communicates
with other systems to provide data on the batterys state and receive
commands. This is essential in applications like electric vehicles, where
the BMS interacts with the motor controller, charging system, and
vehicle management units.
5.3 Measurement and Estimation of Key Parameters
The BMS plays a central role in measuring and estimating several critical
parameters to evaluate and optimize battery performance:
Cell and Pack Voltage: The BMS measures the voltages of individual
cells and the complete pack. These measurements are used to detect
imbalances and avoid overvoltage or undervoltage that could damage
the cells.
Charge/Discharge Current: Measuring current is crucial for esti-
mating the state of charge (SOC) of the battery. Current is monitored
in real-time to avoid overcharging or excessive discharging.
Temperature: The BMS measures the temperature of cells and the
pack to manage overheating risks. If the temperature exceeds a safe
limit, the BMS can limit current or activate a cooling system.
State of Charge (SOC): SOC represents the amount of energy re-
maining in the battery relative to its total capacity. The BMS uses
methods like Coulomb counting or open-circuit voltage to accurately
estimate SOC.
16
State of Health (SOH): SOH reects the batterys ability to store
and deliver energy compared to its initial state. It is estimated by
monitoring the residual capacity and internal resistance of the cells.
An aging battery will show a gradual decrease in SOH, indicating per-
formance loss and potential need for replacement.
5.4 SOC Estimation Algorithms
The estimation of the State of Charge (SOC) of a battery is essential for
the ecient and safe management of battery systems. Several methods ex-
ist, each with its advantages and disadvantages. Here, we will examine the
three main approaches: Coulomb counting, the Open Circuit Voltage (OCV)
method, and the use of an Extended Kalman Filter (EKF).
5.4.1 Coulomb Counting Method
The Coulomb counting method, also known as current integration, is one
of the most commonly used techniques for estimating SOC. It is based on
measuring the current owing in and out of the battery and integrating these
values over time.

5.4.2 Open Circuit Voltage (OCV) Method
The Open Circuit Voltage (OCV) method is a commonly used technique for
estimating SOC. It is based on the direct relationship between the batterys
terminal voltage when it is at rest (no charge or discharge) and its state of
charge. This method is generally more reliable than Coulomb counting but
requires the battery to be at rest for an accurate measurement.

SOC estimation. It combines real-time measurements with a dynamic model

5.5 SOH Estimation Algorithms
Estimating the State of Health (SOH) of a battery is crucial to determine its
aging and ability to function optimally. Several methods exist to evaluate
the SOH, primarily based on the batterys remaining capacity and internal
resistance.
5.5.1 Capacity-Based SOH Estimation
The rst SOH estimation method is based on the batterys capacity, which
decreases over time and usage. Capacity-based SOH is calculated using the
following formula:
SOHcapacity =Current Capacity
Nominal Capacity100
where:
Current Capacity is the measured capacity of the battery at a given
time.
Nominal Capacity is the batterys initial capacity when new.
The current battery capacity evolves over time based on the charging and
discharging current. It can be modeled by integrating the current:
Current Capacity = Previous Capacity + Z(Icharge Idischarge)dt
This approach is commonly used to assess the loss of capacity after mul-
tiple charge and discharge cycles.

5.6 Cell Balancing
Cell balancing is an essential function in Battery Management Systems (BMS),
particularly for battery packs composed of multiple cells connected in series.
The primary objective of balancing is to maintain uniform voltage across the
dierent cells, ensuring better performance and increased battery longevity.
Signicant voltage dierences between cells can lead to performance issues,
safety concerns, and reduced lifespan.
5.6.1 Importance of Balancing
In a battery pack, individual cells may not charge or discharge uniformly due
to slight variations in their capacity, internal resistance, or chemical state.
These dierences can grow over time, causing an imbalance that limits the
overall eciency of the pack. Cell balancing prevents overcharging or exces-
sive discharging of certain cells, which could result in premature degradation,
overheating, or even failure. By keeping cells at similar voltage levels, the
BMS ensures optimal use of the battery pack [?].
5.6.2 Balancing Methods
Cell balancing can be performed in two ways: passive methods or active
methods.
Passive Methods Passive balancing methods dissipate excess energy from
the more charged cells as heat. This is typically done by using resistors
connected to the overcharged cells to discharge them slightly, allowing the
less charged cells to catch up. While simple to implement, this approach is
less energy-ecient because the energy is lost as heat. Passive balancing is
most often used during the battery charging phase [34].
Active Methods Active balancing methods, on the other hand, transfer
energy from the more charged cells to the less charged ones, avoiding energy
loss as heat. This approach is more ecient but also more complex to im-
plement, requiring additional electronic components. Active balancing can
be used during both the charging and discharging phases, allowing for more
precise management of cell states [35].
5.6.3 Cell Balancing States
The balancing process in a BMS is typically divided into several states, with
conditional transitions based on battery and environmental parameters.
23
Initial State: BalancingOFF When balancing is disabled, the system
state is called BalancingOFF. In this state:
Balancing is disabled, and the balancing command (BalCmd) is set to
false.
The voltage dierence between the cells (CellVolt) is calculated but
not used for balancing [36].
Transition to BalancingON Balancing is activated when certain condi-
tions are met:
The balancing activation ag (gEnBalancing) is triggered.
The BMS is not in driving mode (BMS State =BMS Driving).
A certain delay has passed (after(BalOWait, sec)).
The voltage dierence between the cells (CellVolt) exceeds a thresh-
old value (CellVolt >TargetDeltaV) [37].
State: BalancingON Once balancing is activated, the system enters the
BalancingON state. In this state:
The voltage dierence between cells is continuously recalculated.
Cells whose voltage exceeds the target threshold are balanced by acti-
vating the balancing command [38].
Substates of BalancingON The BalancingON state can be subdivided
into two substates:
BalActive: Balancing is active for cells whose voltage exceeds the
threshold. The gBalCompl ag is updated to indicate that balancing
is in progress.
BalNotActive: When balancing is complete or not necessary, the
system transitions to this default state [39].
Transitions Between Substates Transitions between substates are man-
aged as follows:
From BalNotActive to BalActive: After a certain delay and if the
voltage dierence still exceeds the threshold, balancing is activated.
From BalActive to BalNotActive: When balancing is complete (gBal-
Compl ag activated), the system returns to the inactive state [40].
24
Return to BalancingOFF The system returns to the BalancingOFF
state when:
The BMS switches to driving mode.
A predened wait time (BalOnWait) has passed [41].
5.6.4 Summary of Balancing Methods
Passive Methods: Dissipate excess energy from the more charged
cells as heat. Simple but energy inecient. Primarily used during
charging.
Active Methods: Transfer energy between cells, enabling more ef-
cient balancing but more complex to implement. Used during both
charging and discharging [42].
5.7 Current Limitation
Current limitation is a critical function in the Battery Management System
(BMS) that protects the battery from hazardous conditions such as over-
charging, deep discharges, or extreme temperatures. This function ensures
that the current supplied or absorbed by the battery remains within safe
limits, taking into account cell voltage, temperature, and the battery pack
conguration.
General
diagram of current limitation in a BMS
5.7.1 Data Collection
To determine the charge and discharge current limits, the BMS starts by
collecting real-time data from each battery cell. It measures the voltages
(Cell Voltages) and temperatures (Cell Temperatures) of individual cells.
These data are then used to calculate the appropriate current limits, ensuring
that the cells are neither overcharged nor discharged to dangerous levels.
25
5.7.2 Calculation of Minimum and Maximum Values
The block called Calculate Min Max Cells determines the minimum and
maximum values of the cell voltages and temperatures. These values are
essential for setting current limits to protect the most vulnerable cells in the
pack. By identifying the cell with the lowest voltage or highest temperature,
the BMS can set thresholds that consider the most critical conditions within
the pack.
5.7.3 Calculation of Current Limits
Two types of current limits are calculated:
DischargeCurrentLimit: The maximum discharge current the bat-
tery can provide.
ChargeCurrentLimit: The maximum charge current the battery can
accept.
The following image illustrates the calculation of the discharge current limit
(DischargeCurrentLimit):
Discharge
current limit calculation
5.7.4 Determination of the Discharge Current Limit
The discharge current limit (DischargeCurrentLimit) is determined based
on three main factors:
MinCellVoltDchrgCurrentLim: Based on the minimum cell volt-
age, this factor ensures that the cells are not discharged below a critical
threshold.
LowTempDchrgCurrentLim: Based on the minimum cell tempera-
ture, it ensures that the battery is not used when the temperatures are
too low, as this could damage the cells.
HighTempDchrgCurrentLim: Based on the maximum cell temper-
ature, this factor protects the battery from discharges when the tem-
peratures are too high, which could lead to overheating.
26
These three values are compared using a min function, which selects the
most restrictive value, ensuring that the discharge current never exceeds the
limit imposed by the most unfavorable conditions.
5.7.5 Final Adjustment
Once the current limit is calculated, several adjustments can be applied to
ensure optimal current management:
The MaxDchrgCurrLim block can impose an additional maximum
limit, depending on the specic system or application parameters.
The Np Module block adjusts the current limit based on the number
of cells connected in parallel. This allows the load or discharge to be
distributed across multiple cells for more balanced pack usage.
5.7.6 Output: Discharge Current Limit
The output of this system is the nal discharge current limit (DischargeCurrentLimit),
which represents the maximum current the battery can safely deliver. This
limit takes into account the voltage, temperature, and conguration con-
straints of the battery pack, ensuring optimal battery protection.
5.7.7 Conclusion
Current limitation by the BMS plays a crucial role in the safe management
of the battery. It ensures that:
Voltage and temperature constraints are always considered.
The most conservative limit is always applied to protect the weakest
or most vulnerable cells.
The limits are adjusted according to the pack conguration (number
of cells in parallel), ensuring ecient management and maximum per-
formance within safety limits.
This approach protects the battery from overcharging, deep discharges,
and extreme temperature conditions while maximizing performance within
safe limits.

6 Battery Thermal Management
6.1 Importance of Temperature Control
Temperature control is crucial to ensure the proper operation and longevity
of batteries. Temperature variations can signicantly aect the performance,
safety, and lifespan of battery cells. Excessive heat can lead to accelerated
degradation of active materials and an increased risk of overheating or re.
Conversely, too low a temperature can reduce the capacity of cells and in-
crease internal resistance, leading to performance loss and uneven discharge.
An eective thermal management system is therefore essential to maintain
batteries within an optimal temperature range.
6.2 Cooling Methods
To manage the temperature of batteries, several cooling methods can be
employed:
Air Cooling Air cooling is the simplest method, using fans to circulate air
around the batteries and dissipate heat. Although cost-eective, this method
is often insucient for applications requiring more precise thermal control or
for high-capacity batteries.
Liquid Cooling Liquid cooling is more eective for high-power applica-
tions. It uses liquid circuits (often water or a glycol mixture) that circulate
around the batteries to absorb heat and dissipate it via heat exchangers.
This method is more complex to implement but provides better temperature
control.
Phase Change Cooling Phase change cooling systems use materials that
absorb or release heat during physical state changes (solid/liquid). This
technology helps maintain a stable battery temperature by absorbing heat
spikes.
6.3 Thermal Management Strategies
To optimize battery thermal management, several strategies can be imple-
mented:
28
Active Temperature Control Active control uses temperature sensors
and regulation devices to adjust cooling systems in real-time. This ensures
that cell temperatures remain within an optimal range, even under varying
operating conditions.
Predictive Thermal Management Predictive thermal management re-
lies on simulation models and predictive algorithms to anticipate cooling
needs based on charge conditions, ambient temperature, and other parame-
ters. This enables proactive management and avoids overheating situations.
Optimization of Battery Pack Architecture Optimizing the pack ar-
chitecture may include arranging cells to improve airow or distributing liq-
uid cooling channels. A well-designed layout can reduce the need for complex
cooling and improve overall thermal system eciency.
7 Communication and Interface in Battery
Systems
7.1 Communication Protocols (CAN, LIN, etc.)
Communication protocols are essential for exchanging information between
the BMS and other systems or devices. Common protocols include:
CAN (Controller Area Network) The CAN protocol is widely used
in automotive and industrial systems for communication between dierent
controllers. It oers fast and reliable communication, allowing the BMS to
transmit data such as charge states, temperatures, and current limits to other
vehicle modules.
LIN (Local Interconnect Network) The LIN protocol is used for less
complex and lower-cost applications, often complementing CAN. It enables
communication between devices within the BMS and peripheral equipment,
such as displays or climate control systems.
Modbus The Modbus protocol is used in industrial environments for com-
munication between control devices and data management systems. It can be
employed in the BMS for integration with monitoring or energy management
systems.
29
7.2 Interface with the Host System
The interface with the host system enables communication between the BMS
and external systems, such as charge controllers, motor control units, or user
interfaces. This interface must be designed to ensure smooth and reliable
communication, allowing the exchange of critical information and manage-
ment of battery operations.
Communication Interface Communication interfaces may include stan-
dard communication ports such as UART, SPI, or IC, enabling data ex-
change between the BMS and the host system. The design of this interface
should consider communication speed, data security, and compatibility with
existing communication protocols.
Data Logging and Diagnostics Data logging allows storing critical in-
formation on battery performance and system events. The data can include
charge/discharge cycles, temperatures, and detected anomalies. Diagnostics
help identify and resolve potential issues by analyzing this data.
8 Safety and Protection
8.1 Overcharge/Discharge Protection
Protection against overcharge and excessive discharge is essential to avoid
damage to battery cells and ensure system safety. The BMS continuously
monitors charge and discharge levels to ensure they remain within safe limits.
Overcharge Protection The BMS limits the amount of current entering
the battery during charging to prevent overcharging. Voltage thresholds are
set to stop charging when the cells reach their full capacity.
Discharge Protection Similarly, the BMS prevents excessive discharge
by limiting the discharge current when the cell voltage reaches critical levels.
This protects the cells from deep discharge, which could damage the battery.
8.2 Short-Circuit Protection
Short-circuit protection is crucial to prevent potentially severe damage to
cells and the electrical system. The BMS is designed to quickly detect and
30
respond to short-circuits, typically by disconnecting the circuit to prevent
re risks or damage.
8.3 Thermal Protection
Thermal protection includes mechanisms to prevent battery cell overheat-
ing. This can include temperature sensors, cooling systems, and thermal
management algorithms to adjust operating parameters based on measured
temperatures.
8.4 Galvanic Isolation
Galvanic isolation is used to separate electrical circuits to protect battery
management systems from electrical interference and failures. It helps pre-
vent issues related to potential dierences between dierent parts of the
system, ensuring stable and secure operation.

10 Learning and Testing Algorithms for SOH
Estimation
The objective of this study is to develop a model capable of estimating the
State of Health (SOH) of any lithium-ion battery. SOH represents the
health state of the battery based on its ability to store energy relative to its
initial nominal capacity. This model relies on cycling data collected during
34
specic tests at specialized centers, providing insights into the progressive
degradation of batteries over cycles of charge and discharge.
10.1 Input Data
The main input data used for learning and testing the model are as follows:
Nominal voltage: Nominal voltage of the battery (in Volts).
Nominal capacity: Nominal capacity of the battery (in Ah or kWh).
C-rate: Charge/discharge rate (the ratio of charge/discharge current
to the batterys nominal capacity).
Ambient temperature: Ambient temperature (in C) during the
test.
Charge discharge cycles: Number of full charge and discharge cycles
completed on the battery.
10.2 Output Data
The main output data is the State of Health (SOH), expressed as a per-
centage. SOH is a critical indicator of battery performance, as it quanties
the degradation of energy capacity over time. An SOH of 100% indicates
that the battery is in perfect condition, while a lower value signies some
degree of degradation.

10.4 Learning Models Used
For SOH estimation, several machine learning algorithms were evaluated to
identify the one oering the best prediction in terms of accuracy and relia-
bility. The three main models explored are:
1. Linear Regression: This model is useful for identifying linear rela-
tionships between input data and the output (SOH). Although simple
and fast, it may fail to capture all the complex nuances in the data,
especially in the presence of nonlinear relationships.
35
Figure 4: Sample of training data used for SOH prediction.
2. Random Forest: This algorithm is based on a collection of decision
trees. It excels at capturing nonlinear and complex relationships in the
data, making it a frequently reliable choice for SOH prediction. It also
oers robustness against variations in input data.
3. Neural Networks: Neural networks are more advanced models capa-
ble of learning complex structures in the data. They are particularly
useful for problems where nonlinear and hidden relationships between
variables are crucial, although these models may require ne-tuning
and more data to avoid overtting.

pared to the other models.
The neural network may require ne-tuning (hyperparameters, larger
dataset) to improve its performance and avoid overestimation.
10.7 Conclusion
Random Forest: This model appears to be the most eective and ac-
curate for estimating battery SOH. It eectively captures the complex
and nonlinear relationships in the data.
Linear Regression: Although it is quick and simple to implement,
it may not properly model nonlinear relationships but remains a valid
option for quick estimates.
Neural Networks: This model may require more optimization (e.g.,
more data and ne-tuning of hyperparameters) to compete with the
performance of other methods, particularly Random Forest.
In summary, for the specic application of battery SOH estimation, Ran-
dom Forest is recommended for providing accurate and reliable predictions.
